"1220–1258","1221–Male":"1221–Deceased","1231–1287":"1231–1287","1160–1211":"1160–1211","1161–1219":"1161–1219","1220":"1220","1231":"1231","1274":"1274","1185":"1185","1161":"1161","1160":"1160","1217":"1217","1249":"1249","1258":"1258","1269":"1269","1202":"1202","1211":"1211","Abt 1221":"about 1221","1287":"1287","1221":"1221","1265":"1265","1219":"1219","1218":"1218","Moyencourt, Péronne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Moyencourt, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","Conty, Amiens, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Amiens, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","Conty, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Conty, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Conty","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon and Cornwall, of Norman origin): variant of   Cundy  . Compare   Candee  .","French (southern): unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Cundy","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Devon, of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in Normandy and Picardy called Condé, a French form of the Gaulish <i>condate</i> ‘junction of rivers’. Members of the de Condé family held land in Lincolnshire, Kent, Leicestershire, Cambridgeshire, and Yorkshire in the 12th century. The strong presence of the surname in 16th-century Cornwall and Devon is unexpected, but is probably the result of migration from counties further east or north. Derivation from the Cornish language is implausible, and there is no known place in Cornwall which could have given rise to it as a habitational name."]}]},{"name":"Hector","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Name borne in classical legend by the Trojan champion who was killed by the Greek Achilles. His name (Greek <i>Hektōr</i>) is probably an agent derivative of Greek <i>ekhein</i> ‘to restrain’. It was never popular in England, but there are occasional examples from the Middle Ages. In Scotland it was used as a classicized form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Eachann</i>, which is composed of <i>each</i> ‘horse’ + <i>donn</i> ‘brown’. It has been moderately popular in the United States since the 1940s."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hector de Conty was born in 1185, in Amiens, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France, his father, Gauthier de Conty, was 25 and his mother, Giselberthe de Bréteuïl, was 24. He married Ermengarde de Moyencourt in 1217, in Moyencourt, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 3 daughters. He died in 1249, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1185–1249":"1185–1249","1202–1265":"1202–1265","1218–1269":"1218–1269","1219–1274":"1219–1274","1220–1258":"1220–1258","1221–Male":"1221–Surnud","1231–1287":"1231–1287","1160–1211":"1160–1211","1161–1219":"1161–1219","1220":"1220","1231":"1231","1274":"1274","1185":"1185","1161":"1161","1160":"1160","1217":"1217","1249":"1249","1258":"1258","1269":"1269","1202":"1202","1211":"1211","Abt 1221":"umbes 1221","1287":"1287","1221":"1221","1265":"1265","1219":"1219","1218":"1218","Moyencourt, Péronne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Moyencourt, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Conty, Amiens, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Amiens, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusm